"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515281","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>All Ministry of Defence mental health staff have security clearance sufficient to enable them to provide appropriate mental healthcare to any member of the armed forces who requires it. If it were ever assessed that the attendance was required of medical personnel with a specific level of security clearance, arrangements would be made to provide this.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-05-04T13:38:43.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515281/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515281/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Armed Forces: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many medical staff assisting armed forces personnel with stress and other mental health issues are authorised to deal with personnel at each level of security clearance.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","35301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515282","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>The future basing of 7 Commando Battery Royal Artillery, stationed at Royal Marines Condor in Arbroath, is currently under review.</p><p>It is too early to provide details of this review.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-05-04T13:43:42.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515282/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515282/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Royal Artillery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the options are for the location of 7 Commando Battery Royal Artillery; and by what criteria the location of that regiment will be determined.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","35304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515283","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>The MOD uses hire and lease vehicles to transport personnel and equipment around the country, often to areas not readily accessible by public transport. The vehicles are used for different tasks, ranging from moving defence personnel and stores to support military operations or training exercises, to enabaling taskings such as mountain rescue and emergency support to the civil authorities.</p><p>The MOD’s vehicle lease and hire in the UK is covered by the Phoenix contract with Babcock Land Limited, which was placed in April 2012. The department does not hold readily available and comparative spend data before this date. The cost to the MOD of vehicle lease and hire through the Phoenix contract is as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>FY15/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY14/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY13/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY12/13</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£124.1m</p></td><td><p>£132.4m</p></td><td><p>£125.5m</p></td><td><p>£101.9m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The MOD recently negotiated a new contract with Babcock Land Limited for the continued provision of its lease and hire cars, targeting savings of around £100m over the next six years through more efficient use of the MOD’s vehicle fleet.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-04T16:58:36.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515283/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515283/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Ministry of Defence: Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to his Department was of vehicle hire in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","35302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515284","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>Between 1 April 2015 and 31 March 2016, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) has reported that 39 laptops were lost.</p><p>The MOD treats all losses of assets seriously. All reported losses are subjected to an initial security risk assessment, with further action taken on a proportionate basis.</p><p>It is MOD policy that its laptops are to be encrypted to minimise the impact if a loss were to occur.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-05-04T13:42:22.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515284/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515284/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Ministry of Defence: Computers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many of his Department's laptop computers have been lost in the last year.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","35303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515285","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-28","<p>NATO is not conducting any operations in the South Central Mediterranean and has therefore not rescued any people attempting to cross the Mediterranean from North Africa.</p><p> </p><p>The main countries of origin of people attempting to cross the Mediterranean from North Africa and rescued by EU and UK maritime operations are the following:</p><p> </p><p>Algeria</p><p>Cameroon</p><p>Eritrea</p><p>Ethiopia</p><p>Ghana</p><p>Gambia</p><p>Guinea</p><p>Ivory Coast</p><p>Mali</p><p>Morocco</p><p>Nigeria</p><p>Senegal</p><p>Somalia</p><p>Sudan</p><p> </p><p>The only UK maritime operation over the last two years in the Central Mediterranean was conducted in May and June 2015, where HMS BULWARK rescued 4,747 persons from the following nationalities:</p><p> </p><p>Benin</p><p>Burkina Faso</p><p>Cameroon</p><p>Chad</p><p>Ethiopia</p><p>Eretria</p><p>The Gambia</p><p>Ghana</p><p>Guinea</p><p>Ivory Coast</p><p>Kenya</p><p>Libya</p><p>Mali</p><p>Morocco</p><p>Nigeria</p><p>Pakistan</p><p>Senegal</p><p>Sudan</p><p> </p><p>We do not centrally hold information on the nationalities of persons rescued by NATO or EU operations in the Central Mediterranean. The FRONTEX website does have information about numbers and nationalities of migrants attempting to cross the Central Mediterranean from North Africa.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-04-28T15:19:24.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515285/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515285/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the country of origin was of people attempting to cross the Mediterranean from North Africa who were intercepted by (a) NATO (b) EU and (c) UK maritime operations in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","35361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515286","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>At this stage, it is too early to comment on any potential names for the two additional River Class Offshore Patrol Vessels.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-04T13:56:09.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515286/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515286/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Patrol Craft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Strategic Defence and Security Review, whether names have been found for the two additional river class offshore patrol vessels.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","35320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515287","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-28","<p>The UK Deputy Permanent Representative to NATO attended the NATO-Russia Council on 20 April 2016. Allies stood firm and united in denouncing Russia's illegal actions in Ukraine. In annexing Ukraine's land, violating its territorial integrity, and destabilising east Ukraine, Russia has contravened international law and challenged the rules based international order.</p><p>The meeting also discussed military transparency and risk reduction, and the security situation in Afghanistan. Political channels of communication will remain open, but NATO is clear that there will be no return to 'business as usual' until Russia respects international law.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-04-28T15:18:24.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515287/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515287/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Russia: NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether a Government representative attended the meeting of the NATO-Russia Council held in April 2016; and what the conclusions of that meeting were.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","35344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515288","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>The contract to build the two additional Offshore Patrol Vessels referred to in the White Paper National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 has yet to be awarded.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-04T15:06:03.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515288/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515288/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Patrol Craft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will place in the Library copies of the contracts signed for the construction of the two additional river class offshore patrol vessels between his Department and BAE Systems.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","35321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515289","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>Since 2011, there have been around 50 visits by defence delegations from foreign countries to the Queen Elizabeth Class Aircraft Carriers being built in Rosyth, reflecting the broad range of organisations from Allies and partner nations with a legitimate interest in the programme.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-04T13:56:42.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515289/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515289/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many defence delegations from foreign countries have visited the construction site of the Queen Elizabeth-class aircraft carriers.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","35394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515290","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>Veterans UK has written to existing War Disablement Pension claimants with mesothelioma to inform them of the new option of a lump sum. In addition to the announcements I made in this House on 16 December 2015 (Official Report, column 1629) and 29 February 2016 (Official Report, column 667), news stories were posted by the Ministry of Defence on the gov.uk website. At the same time we informed ex-Service organisations and asbestos support groups for them to bring the change to the attention of their members.</p><p>We have also provided information on the War Pensions Scheme and new lump sum for mesothelioma to NHS England and the Devolved Administrations for the awareness of GPs.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-05-04T14:16:15.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515290/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515290/answer","Hansard Extracts  HOC 35375.docx","Hansard Extracts  HOC 35375.docx","Mesothelioma","Mesothelioma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515290/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Veterans: Mesothelioma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of his Department's ability to identify all veterans with mesothelioma.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","35375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515291","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>On 5 September 2014 at the NATO Summit in Cardiff, the Prime Minister announced that the second carrier, would be brought into service, ensuring that we always have one carrier available, 100% of the time. This decision was re-affirmed in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review. There is, therefore, no plan to sell one of the Queen Elizabeth Class Carriers to a foreign country.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-04T13:57:36.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515291/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515291/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Aircraft Carriers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government has plans to sell one of the Queen Elizabeth-class aircraft carriers to a foreign country.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","35395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515292","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-28","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Dunfermline and West Fife (Douglas Chapman) to Question 32497 on 11 April 2016.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-04-28T16:07:02.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515292/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515292/answer","Hansard_Extract_11_April_2016,_HOC32497[1].docx","Hansard_Extract_11_April_2016,_HOC32497[1].docx","32497 - QnA extract on Type 26 Frigates","32497 - QnA extract on Type 26 Frigates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515292/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Frigates: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the current timetable is for the procurement of manufacturing of Type 26 frigates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","35482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515293","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Disposal Services Authority (DSA) accounts are prepared in accordance with the Ministry of Defence Financial Accounting Processes and Procedures; the DSA reports financial receipts rather than profit.</p><p>DSA equipment disposal receipts for the last three full financial years are provided in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Net Receipts (£ million)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>39.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>44.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>29.2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note: Net receipts change year-on-year, dependent on what equipment is declared surplus to requirement.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-04T13:58:08.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515293/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515293/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Disposal Services Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the profits made by the Disposal Services Authority were in (a) 2012-13, (b) 2013-14 and (c) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","35457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515294","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-28","<p>We have begun the initial work to take forward the new General Purpose Frigate programme outlined in the White Paper 'National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015'. The work is in the very early stages and it is too soon to say what the procurement timetable will be.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-04-28T16:08:37.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515294/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515294/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Frigates: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the timetable is for the procurement of general purpose frigates; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","35481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515295","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-28","<p>The National Shipbuilding Strategy is intended to place UK shipbuilding on a sustainable long-term footing. It will look at how to build a new complex warship on a regular schedule and maximise export opportunities in order to deliver capable ships and value for money, as well as maintaining jobs and skills. It will ensure that the Royal Navy continues to have the capability it needs to protect our nation's interests, retaining its status as the most modern Navy in the world. Sir John Parker has been appointed as the Independent Chair of the Strategy. He will bring strong strategic direction and guidance to the work, and report to Ministers. He will lead the high level engagement with key stakeholders.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-04-28T16:09:48.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515295/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515295/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Warships: Shipbuilding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the terms of reference are for the National Shipbuilding Strategy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","35480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515296","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) defines the commercial exploitation levy as a form of royalty for any commercial sales of a design, use of special tooling or the granting of licences where the MOD has contributed to research and development costs. There are no restrictions on the categories of contracts to which the levy applies, but the vast majority relate to equipment, including software. This is because MOD research and development funding is largely in support of equipment development.</p><p> </p><p>The general aim of levy arrangements should be to take a consistent, simple and quick approach to obtaining the maximum return possible without harming sales. It is negotiated on a contract by contract basis and represents either a percentage of sales or a profit sharing agreement.</p><p> </p><p>The amount of levy received during the financial years requested is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>£ million (Ex-VAT)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>8.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>8.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>12.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-05-04T13:41:57.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515296/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515296/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-25","Defence: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how his Department defines the commercial exploitation levy; and how much was received by his Department from that levy in financial years (a) 2012-13, (b) 2013-14 and (c) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","35405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515297","Department for Education","false","2016-05-04","<p>The estimated number of educational psychologists who will retire in the next five years is outlined in table 1. This is based on the number of educational psychologists registered to work in England, collated by the Health and Care Professions Council[1]. The data is for the workforce as a whole and does not distinguish between where educational psychologists are working.</p><p><strong>Table 1</strong> The estimated number of educational psychologists who will retire and the number of newly qualified who will enter the profession, in the next five years.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number reaching retirement age (65)</strong></p></td><td><p>84</p></td><td><p>94</p></td><td><p>97</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>95</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Newly qualified entering the profession</strong></p></td><td><p>127[2]</p></td><td><p>128</p></td><td><p>131</p></td><td><p>150</p></td><td><p>150</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: Health and Care Professions Council (2015) and NCTL (2016)</em></p><p> </p><p>[1] Health and Care professions Council <a href="http://www.hcpc-uk.co.uk/" target="_blank">www.<strong>hcpc</strong>-uk.co.uk</a></p><p>[2] This may increase to 132 depending on the number of deferral / maternity leave trainee who re-join the course in year three.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-04T10:52:02.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515297/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515297/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-25","Educational Psychology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of publicly employed educational psychologists who will retire in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","35382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515298","Department for Education","false","2016-04-28","<p>Regional Schools Commissioners discuss the options for schools to convert to academy status with local authorities on a regular basis – and in the case of underperforming schools in particular, those discussions focus on which multi-academy trusts are the most effective way of securing sustainable improvement.</p><p>The White Paper <em>Educational Excellence Everywhere</em> makes clear that we want to ensure that we make best use of talented staff currently within local authorities to establish or join multi-academy trusts. Our discussions with local authorities will continue to look at the options available to harness that talent.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-04-28T16:36:56.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515298/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515298/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-25","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with which local authorities her Department has held discussions on the possibility of local authorities running multi-academy trusts.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","35427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515299","Department for Education","false","2016-05-11","<p>Since the free schools programme began, 81 free school projects have had their opening date deferred. In each case there was a need to balance the risk of opening on the planned date against all the elements that must be in place to ensure that a free school is successful when it opens. Our guidance makes clear that allowing a free school project to enter the “pre-opening” phase does not guarantee that the school will open on the date originally planned by the proposer group, or open at all.</p><p><br> Free schools offer excellent value for money. The National Audit Office found in 2013 that free schools were built 45% more cheaply than other school building programmes. The free schools that are already open will provide over 150,000 new places.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-05-11T16:42:04.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515299/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515299/answer","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515299/answer/previousversion/58197","Biography information for Edward Timpson","60","Education","Education","2016-04-25","Free Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many free schools were delayed in opening in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","35436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515300","Department for Education","false","2016-05-04","<p>The transition period from statements to Education, Health and Care plans (EHCPs) runs until April 2018. Every local authority has published an individual Local Transition Plan setting out the timings for transfers to the new system. We are monitoring local authority progress and published figures about transition up to January 2015, returned by local authorities, in the Special Educational Needs in England Statistical First Release of May 2015[1]. We will publish the figures up to January 2016 in May 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not collect information on the number of children who are home educated. Some local authorities choose to maintain registers so that parents can voluntarily register children being educated at home.</p><p> </p><p>The number and proportion of school pupils who had a Statement of Special Educational Needs or an EHCP in each of the last five years is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>x</p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils with statements or EHCPs</p></td><td><p>224,210</p></td><td><p>226,125</p></td><td><p>229,390</p></td><td><p>232,190</p></td><td><p>236,165</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Pupils on roll</p></td><td><p>8,123,865</p></td><td><p>8,178,200</p></td><td><p>8,249,810</p></td><td><p>8,331,385</p></td><td><p>8,438,145</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Incidence (%)</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td><td><p>2.8</p></td><td><p>2.8[2]</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The number of permanent and fixed period exclusions received by pupils with a Statement of Special Educational Needs in each of the last five years for which data is available is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>x</p></td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fixed period exclusions</p></td><td><p>37,140</p></td><td><p>36,740</p></td><td><p>35,640</p></td><td><p>32,210</p></td><td><p>33,190</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Permanent exclusions</p></td><td><p>420</p></td><td><p>430</p></td><td><p>380</p></td><td><p>330</p></td><td><p>330[3]</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen</a></p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2015</a></p><p>[3] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-exclusions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-exclusions</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","35386 ; 35387 ; 35388","2016-05-04T10:58:33.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515300/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515300/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-25","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many local authorities have completed the task of transferring all statements of special educational needs to Education, Health and Care Plans to date; and what assessment she has made of whether the deadline of 2017 will be met by all local authorities.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","35384"
