"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515408","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-03","<p>The UK has committed £79.5 million of humanitarian assistance to Iraq since summer 2014. This includes cash assistance, access to clean water, food, medicines and other life-saving assistance for the most vulnerable. Our partners distribute our aid on the basis of need across Iraq, including to internally displaced persons in northern Iraq.</p><p>Given the importance of a coordinated response, we are providing funding to UNDP to support the Kurdistan Regional Government’s (KRG) Joint Crisis Centre (JCC), as well as its equivalent for the Government of Iraq, the Joint Crisis and Monitoring Centre (JCMC). In close collaboration with the JCMC, UN, donors and NGOs, the JCC is leading humanitarian efforts for the KRG.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","35374","2016-05-03T12:34:51.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515408/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515408/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Kurds: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department has taken to assist the Kurdistan region.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","35373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515409","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-03","<p>The UK has committed £79.5 million of humanitarian assistance to Iraq since summer 2014. This includes cash assistance, access to clean water, food, medicines and other life-saving assistance for the most vulnerable. Our partners distribute our aid on the basis of need across Iraq, including to internally displaced persons in northern Iraq.</p><p>Given the importance of a coordinated response, we are providing funding to UNDP to support the Kurdistan Regional Government’s (KRG) Joint Crisis Centre (JCC), as well as its equivalent for the Government of Iraq, the Joint Crisis and Monitoring Centre (JCMC). In close collaboration with the JCMC, UN, donors and NGOs, the JCC is leading humanitarian efforts for the KRG.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","35373","2016-05-03T12:34:51.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515409/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515409/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Iraq: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to assist internally displaced persons in northern Iraq with humanitarian aid.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","35374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515410","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-28","<p>DFID will be running a Graduate Development Scheme for 2016. Recruitment is due to launch in May 2016.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-28T13:42:20.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515410/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515410/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Department for International Development: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department's Graduate Development Scheme will take place in 2016; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","35274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515411","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-03","<p>The UK condemns the blockage of medical evacuations from hard to reach and besieged areas inside Syria, which has led to unnecessary death and suffering. In March 2016, for example, three children and a young man in Madaya and al-Wa’er died after having their evacuations rejected by the parties restricting access to these towns. Access to healthcare and medical treatment is a fundamental human right protected under international law.</p><p>Some progress is being made. For example, we are pleased by UN reports that nearly 500 people were evacuated for medical reasons from besieged areas on 20 April.</p><p>However, more needs to be done to provide for all those in need in Syria. The UK is pressing for an end to the removal of medical equipment from convoys by the regime, the evacuation of critical medical cases and regular access to healthcare for besieged populations. We will continue to use our position in the UN Security Council and the International Syria Support Group to draw attention to the atrocities being carried out in Syria and press for urgent action, while maintaining the pressure for a political settlement to bring the suffering of the Syrian people to an end.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-03T12:34:28.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515411/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515411/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34222, on the humanitarian situation in Madaya, what estimate she has made of the number of civilian deaths due to blocked medical evacuations.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","35216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515412","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-03","<p>The UK plays a key role in opening up humanitarian access in Syria. At least 280 shipments of cross-border aid have been delivered because of the UK co-sponsored UN Security Council Resolutions 2165, 2191 and 2258.</p><p>The Department for International Development works closely with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) as part of a whole of government response to the Syria crisis. The FCO are raising issues of humanitarian access across Syria with their Russian counterparts at every opportunity.</p><p>We continue to use our position in the UN Security Council and the International Syria Support Group to call on all sides to the conflict and their backers – including Russia - to respect International Humanitarian Law (IHL) and to ensure free, unimpeded access for humanitarian agencies.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-03T12:34:07.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515412/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515412/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34222, on the humanitarian situation in Madaya, what discussions she has had with her Russian counterpart about humanitarian access across Syria.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","35215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515413","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-03","<p>It is unacceptable that medical items are being systematically removed from humanitarian convoys inside Syria, the vast majority by the Assad Regime. According to the UN, 80,000 medical treatments were excluded or removed from their convoys in February 2016 alone. Items removed include essential life-saving medical items such as surgical and anaesthetic supplies and blood bags. These are exactly the items that are vital to treat victims of bombings or shelling, as well as essential to treat accidental trauma and for Caesarean sections or some complicated deliveries. Other items such as diarrhoea kits, emergency health kits, antibiotics, and other medicines have been removed.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to use our position in the UN Security Council and the International Syria Support Group to press for an end to the removal of medical equipment from convoys by the Regime, the evacuation of critical medical cases and regular access to healthcare for besieged populations.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-03T12:33:00.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515413/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515413/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34222, on the humanitarian situation in Madaya, what medical equipment has been removed from convoys by the Syrian regime.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","35214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515414","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-03","<p>Attempting to deliver humanitarian assistance without the consent of the parties to the conflict is extremely challenging. There is a risk that shipments of humanitarian assistance would be physically stopped and confiscated, humanitarian staff placed in danger and that convoys could come under attack. Likewise, delivering assistance without consent may risk undermining ongoing negotiations on humanitarian access to the 4.6 million people in hard to reach areas across Syria.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-03T12:32:33.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515414/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515414/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34222, on the humanitarian situation in Madaya, for what reasons the UN had to seek written approval from the Syrian regime.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","35212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515415","Department for International Development","false","2016-05-03","<p>We are relieved that, as a result of the work of the International Syria Support Group, humanitarian convoys have reached over 220,000 - 45% - of the 487,000 people living in besieged areas since February 2016. However, progress is too slow. In particular, the Syrian Regime has still not granted approval for convoys to the besieged areas of Duma, East Harasta and Darayya, all of which are in dire need and mere minutes’ drive away from UN warehouses in Damascus.</p><p>Reasons cited by the regime for not authorising access include the lack of civilians in these areas as well as their inability to guarantee security for humanitarian actors. However, reports from humanitarian actors, including the UN, demonstrate the significant presence of civilians in areas to which access has been denied. For example, on a recent mission to besieged Darayya on 16 April, the UN reported the presence of thousands of civilians including women and children. In addition, whilst we recognise the importance of security concerns, experience in other besieged areas demonstrates that these populations can be reached safely.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-05-03T12:33:46.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515415/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515415/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-25","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34222, on the humanitarian situation in Madaya, for what reasons approval was not given for aid convoys to access five of the eleven besieged locations.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","35213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515416","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-03","<p>My Department currently has no general plans to allow web users to include honours when completing on line forms.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-05-03T09:10:59.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515416/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515416/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-25","Ministry of Justice: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34465, if his Department will take steps to allow web-users to include honours when completing Government online forms.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","35209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515417","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-03","<p>Excluding one closing court, in Lancashire all criminal courts (4 Crown courts and 6 magistrates’ courts) are equipped to work digitally through services such as in-court evidence presentation, video links, a shared file store, Wi-Fi and a new digital case management system in the Crown courts.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-05-03T09:26:17.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515417/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515417/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-25","Courts: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many e-courts there are in Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","35287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515418","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-05-03","<p>Two court buildings in Lancashire have been sold since the creation of HM Court Service in 2005. Neither of these were in Burnley.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to 2005 magistrates’ courts were the responsibility of locally managed magistrates’ courts committees.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-05-03T09:36:40.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515418/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515418/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-25","Courts: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many court buildings have been sold in (a) Lancashire and (b) Burnley.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","35288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515419","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-28","<p>As of 31 December 2015 there were 9,895 Foreign National Offenders (FNOs) held in prisons and NOMS-operated Immigration Removal Centres, of which 6,612 were sentenced prisoners. Of these: 1,312 were sentenced for drug offences; 1,084 of these were sentenced for sexual offences; and, 258 of these were sentenced for fraud offences.</p><p> </p><p>This government has a longstanding policy to do everything possible to return foreign prisoners to their home country at the earliest opportunity. Since 2010, 29,000 FNOs have been removed from the UK, with the total FNO population in our prisons reducing from 10,866 in December 2010 to 9,895 in December 2015. Offender management statistics, including FNOs, can be found at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-28T10:11:55.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515419/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515419/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-25","Prisoners: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many foreign national offenders in prison have been convicted of (a) drugs, (b) sexual violence and (c) fraud offences.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","35472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515420","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-28","<p>As I told the House on 26<sup>th</sup> April, the Government’s position on the European Convention of Human Rights remains clear. We cannot rule out withdrawing forever, but our forthcoming proposals do not include it.</p><p> </p><p>We are confident that we can replace the Human Rights Act with a Bill of Rights and reform our relationship with the Strasbourg Court.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-04-28T16:38:31.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515420/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515420/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-25","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his policy is on UK membership of the European Convention on Human Rights; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","35438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515421","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-28","<p>This Government was elected with a mandate to reform and modernise the UK human rights framework. We engage with all relevant government departments on a regular basis at Ministerial and official level. Reform of the UK’s human rights framework involves careful consideration within government and our proposals will be published in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-04-28T11:48:03.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515421/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515421/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-25","European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he last discussed the European Convention on Human Rights with the Secretary of State for the Home Department.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","35433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515422","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-04-29","<p>Prosecutions relating to cross-border fuel smuggling and laundering are a matter for HM Revenue and Customs, whose policy is to arrest individuals where there is evidence that they have been involved in fuel fraud, as long as this is proportionate.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Executive, under the Fresh Start Agreement, is implementing additional measures aimed at tackling the impact of criminality and paramilitarism in Northern Ireland. That includes the establishment of a new cross-jurisdictional joint agency task force with a focus on a range of crimes, including fuel smuggling and laundering.</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-04-29T10:31:57.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515422/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515422/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-04-25","Smuggling: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with HM Revenue and Customs on the level of prosecutions relating to cross-border fuel smuggling and laundering.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","35315"
