"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515424","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-05-03","<p>Defra has recently submitted detailed evidence required by the US authorities. My Right Honourable friend the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs was recently in Washington DC to raise the importance of this agreement. We continue to press for expeditious consideration of the UK application to allow exports of UK beef and lamb to commence as soon as possible.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-05-03T09:35:46.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515424/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515424/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-25","Meat: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of when the ban on the export of Welsh beef and lamb to the US is likely to be lifted.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","35307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515425","Prime Minister","false","2016-05-02","<p>President Obama and I discussed a wide range of issues including promoting the increased free trade between the EU and US. At the same time the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs was in Washington DC meeting the US Secretary of Agriculture to discuss opening the US market to the exports of UK beef and lamb.</p><p> </p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-05-02T13:05:51.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515425/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515425/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-04-25","Meat: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether he discussed the ban on the export of Welsh lamb and beef to the US with President Obama during his recent visit.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","35308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515426","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Department’s estimated incremental cost of preparing and publishing the Shaw Report is £875,919.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-28T13:28:29.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515426/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515426/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 10 March 2016 to Question 30100, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to the public purse of preparing and publishing the Shaw Report: Final Report and Recommendations, published on 16 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","35330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515427","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Department, Network Rail and HS2 Ltd are currently working together to produce a plan to progress the initial feasibility and business case work needed for this project over the next two years, which will include the timing, resource required, and estimated cost. We expect to complete this plan by Summer 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-28T13:35:00.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515427/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515427/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Euston Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 14 April 2016 to Question 33386, when he expects that the work to produce a plan to progress the initial feasibility and business case for a Euston Station masterplan will be completed.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","35329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515428","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-03","<p>The Department for Transport has no powers to oversee or direct Competent Harbour Authorities in the execution of their duties to provide pilotage services in accordance with the 1987 Pilotage Act.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-03T13:11:24.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515428/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515428/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Pilotage Act 1987","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the role of his Department is in overseeing the operation of the Pilotage Act 1987 and in ensuring compliance with the provisions of that Act.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","35313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515429","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>It is a Competent Harbour Authority which has the statutory duty to determine what pilotage services need to be provided to secure the safety of navigation of vessels operating in their waters. Where a ruling on the legality of its actions is needed, that is a matter for the court rather than the Department.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T11:10:59.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515429/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515429/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Pilotage Act 1987","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what mechanisms his Department has put in place for responding to allegations that a competent harbour authority has not acted in conformity with the provisions of the Pilotage Act 1987.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","35314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515430","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Maritime Accident Investigation Branch (MAIB) report into the sinking of the Cemfjord was published on the 21 April. The Maritime &amp; Coastguard Agency (MCA) is carefully considering the recommendations about maritime safety information, ship reporting and routeing, and monitoring.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>None of the recommendations in the MAIB report are addressed specifically to the Department. However, the Department takes these findings, and those from other MAIB reports, into consideration in the development of policy and in its interactions in international forums on these issues.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-28T13:39:48.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515430/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515430/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Shipping: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policy of the recommendations by the Maritime Accident Investigation Branch in its review of the sinking of the Cemfjord; what discussions his Department has had with the Maritime Coastguard Agency on implementing those recommendations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","35277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515431","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>My Department provides a wide variety of online forms across multiple systems. Most of these are designed to enable web users to use perform a transaction, such as to book a driving theory test. Therefore we only ask our users the minimum information required to process their requests to enable them to complete these transactions as quickly as possible.</p><p> </p><p>I am mindful that there could be an additional cost to the taxpayer in making changes to online systems to capture and store additional data.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:48:48.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515431/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515431/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Department for Transport: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34465, if his Department will take steps to allow web-users to include honours when completing Government online forms.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","35210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515432","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>There are no plans to make the Port Marine Safety Code mandatory. The non-statutory status of the Code is vital to its success, enabling port operators to apply industry-agreed good practice flexibly in ways most appropriate to the size and operations of their facility.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T11:07:20.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515432/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515432/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Ports: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals on the Port and Marine Safety Code.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","35250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515433","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>We regularly assess all threats to aviation security along with appropriate response measures. Following the recent attacks at Brussels Airport, measures were put in place to enhance the protection of public areas at UK airports. We do not currently assess that requiring all bags to be scanned at the entrance to airport building would be an effective and proportionate response, but we will continue to work with airports and the police to keep this and other possible measures under review.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-28T13:43:20.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515433/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515433/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Aviation: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the security of airports of security scanning all bags before they are allowed into an airport building.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","35266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515434","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-03","<p>Under the Pilotage Act 1987, it is Competent Harbour Authority’s duty to keep under review what pilotage services are needed for safe navigation and to provide those services accordingly, for which a proper assessment of the interests of safety is relevant as spelt out in the <em>Sea Empress</em> case.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-03T14:20:14.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515434/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515434/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Pilotage Act 1987","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how his Department observes the Sea Empress ruling in its observation of the Pilotage Act 1987; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","35249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515435","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-03","<p>The 2015 Spending Review reconfirmed the Government’s commitment to the programme providing a long-term funding envelope of £55.7bn in 2015 prices. A breakdown of this envelope with and without contingency has been provided below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>£'bn, 2015 Prices</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Phase One</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Phase 2a</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Phase 2b</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Rolling Stock</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Without Contingency</p></td><td><p>18.0</p></td><td><p>2.7</p></td><td><p>14.7</p></td><td><p>5.4</p></td><td><p>40.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>With Contingency</p></td><td><p>24.3</p></td><td><p>3.7</p></td><td><p>20.7</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>55.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-03T10:02:41.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515435/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515435/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much of the current £55.7 billion budget for High Speed 2 is for (a) phase 1, (b) phase 2A and (c) phase 2B; and what the contingency budget is for each such phase.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515436","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>HS2 Ltd and the Department for Transport have been analysing route and station options in light of the responses received following the Phase Two consultation.</p><p> </p><p>We have also been considering Sir David Higgins’ proposals to bring forward the benefits of HS2 to the North with a new Crewe Hub station, improve connectivity between Northern cities, and further integrate with Network Rail’s Strategic Business Plan, before deciding how to proceed.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Phase Two remains on target to open in 2033.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T12:52:07.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515436/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515436/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the reasons were for the delay in announcing the route of phase 2B of High Speed 2 to Manchester and Leeds.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515437","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-03","<p>We expect to announce the Government’s response to the HS2 Phase Two: West Midlands to Crewe Property (Phase 2a) Consultation 2015 by the summer Recess.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-03T10:37:36.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515437/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515437/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce the package of compensation schemes for phase 2A of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515438","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-03","<p>We support the development of cycle hubs that have all the facilities a cyclist needs in one place and are providing funding for a number of these hubs. We have already financed a number of these innovative hubs which have contributed towards the number of cycle parking spaces across England trebling since 2012.</p><p> </p><p>We are monitoring with interest the development of the cycle superhub at Waterloo Station which will provide cycle parking on a much larger scale to ascertain the effectiveness of such a facility at other cities across England.</p><p> </p><p>Cycling is a devolved responsibility for Scotland and Wales.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-03T13:14:57.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515438/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515438/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he supports the expansion of centres such as Travel for London's planned cycling superhub to other parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","35240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515439","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-03","<p>The Government is aware of the public concern at the way some private parking companies operate.</p><p>Whilst we have not held any specific discussions with the DVLA or representatives of the private parking companies, we are currently reviewing responses to the discussion paper, “Parking Reform: Tackling Unfair Practices”.</p><p>We will issue a response in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","35229","2016-05-03T14:48:24.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515439/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515439/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-25","Parking Offences: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the DVLA on the implications of the Supreme Court case, Beavis vs ParkingEye.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","35230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515440","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-03","<p>The Government is aware of the public concern at the way some private parking companies operate.</p><p>Whilst we have not held any specific discussions with the DVLA or representatives of the private parking companies, we are currently reviewing responses to the discussion paper, “Parking Reform: Tackling Unfair Practices”.</p><p>We will issue a response in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","35230","2016-05-03T14:48:24.38Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515440/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515440/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-25","Parking Offences: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with representatives of the private parking industry on the implications of the Supreme Court case, Beavis vs ParkingEye.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","35229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515441","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>I anticipate this consultation will be published in the summer and will run for 12 weeks.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-04T11:14:44.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515441/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515441/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Motor Vehicles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 24 November 2015 to Question 16881, when the consultation on extending the deadline for new cars and motorbikes to have their first MOT test from three to four years will begin.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","35412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515442","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>The criteria for Public Service Obligations (PSOs) are determined by regulations agreed at the European level. We are carefully considering the Airports Commission’s recommendation to extend the scope of PSOs.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T11:55:22.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515442/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515442/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Aviation: Public Service Obligations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 25 April 2016 to Question 34715, and with reference to paragraph 15.20 of the Airports Commission: Final Report, published in July 2015, what response he has made to the Airports Commission's recommendation that the Government should alter its guidance to allow public service obligation subsidies that specify airports both origin and destination.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","35413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515443","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>No intrusive ground investigation work has been carried out at this stage. Some preparatory elements of ground investigation such as the study of available information and consultation with related stakeholders has been undertaken.</p><p> </p><p>Following a route decision in autumn 2016 HS2 Ltd will begin production of a full Environmental Impact Assessment.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:45:34.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515443/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515443/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether any ground investigation work has been carried out in Eddisbury constituency in relation to the High Speed 2 project.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515444","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Government is responsible for the legislative structure within which local licensing authorities deliver the licensing regime for taxis and private hire vehicles. Enforcement of the licensing regime, including ensuring that private hire vehicles do not illegally ply for hire, is therefore a matter for local licensing authorities and the police.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-28T15:59:25.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515444/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515444/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Taxis: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to maintain the ability of London taxi drivers exclusively to ply for hire.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","35449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515445","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>Private hire vehicles cannot legally ply for hire.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is responsible for the legislative structure within which local licensing authorities deliver the licensing regime for taxis and private hire vehicles. Enforcement of the licensing regime, including ensuring that private hire vehicles do not illegally ply for hire, is a matter for local licensing authorities and the police.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-28T16:02:11.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515445/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515445/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on allowing private hire cars to ply for hire.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","35451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515446","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>Aerial surveys were undertaken in this area in 2015 to capture photography, video and topographical information. Additional surveys will be undertaken in 2016 to capture hyperspectral data.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:38:47.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515446/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515446/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether any aerial surveys have been carried out in Eddisbury constituency in relation to the High Speed 2 project in 2015 and 2016.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515447","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Department’s most recent published road traffic forecast for England was published in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Compared to the traffic volumes in 2014, the latest year for which traffic statistics are available for England, the Department forecasts that traffic volumes will be:</p><p>a) 4-20% higher in 2020</p><p>b) 11-38% higher in 2030</p><p>c) 15-52% higher in 2040</p><p>More detailed information can be found on the Department for Transport pages on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-28T15:56:06.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515447/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515447/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Road Traffic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the change in total traffic volumes across the entire road network over present levels by (a) 2020, (b) 2030 and (c) 2040.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","35474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515448","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-03","<p>The Department has appointed a joint team of solicitors/parliamentary agents from Winckworth Sherwood and Eversheds LLP to provide support in relation to the HS2 Phase One hybrid Bill. The value of the contract as agreed with Cabinet Office’s Efficiency and Reform Group is £10.5m. The contract duration is from March 2012 until six months after Royal Assent.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has also appointed a joint team of solicitors/parliamentary agents from Winckworth Sherwood and Eversheds LLP to support the preparation of the HS2 Phase 2a hybrid bill, which is expected to be deposited in 2017. The value of the contract as agreed with Cabinet Office’s Efficiency and Reform Group is £4.2m over three years, with the opportunity to extend the contract for an additional one or two years, subject to approval.</p><p> </p><p>The Department also continues to instruct a number of barristers to support the HS2 project. However, the use of barristers is demand led and so the total cost of fees over the next five years is not possible to forecast.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-03T13:55:02.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515448/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515448/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what forecast his Department has made of the cost of legal fees for the High Speed 2 project over the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","35372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515449","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>No intrusive geological surveys have been carried out at this stage. HS2 Ltd has commissioned from a mining engineer (in consultation with the Cheshire Brine Subsidence Compensation Board) a study of the historical subsidence effects and ongoing extractive processes in relation to salt. This includes review of ground movements in the time between two successive (2014 and 2015) HS2 LIDAR surveys of the route in Cheshire, and earlier where relevant third party LIDAR data has been made available.</p><p> </p><p>A re-review of the usefulness of satellite interferometry to evaluate historical ground movement across Cheshire (including the Eddisbury constituency) is ongoing.</p><p> </p><p>Following a route decision in autumn 2016 HS2 Ltd will begin production of a full Environmental Impact Assessment.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:32:30.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515449/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515449/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which geological surveys undertaken by HS2 Ltd since 17 July 2013 have considered (a) subsidence and (b) the effects of shifting land movement owing to salt movement or other effects of salt mining in Eddisbury constituency.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515450","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>No field mapping has been carried out except two successive (2014 and 2015) HS2 LiDAR surveys of the route in Cheshire.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Ltd has commissioned from a mining engineer (in consultation with the Cheshire Brine Subsidence Compensation Board) a study of the saltfield, including the location of known brine wells.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Ltd has consulted with brine/salt extraction stakeholders in the Eddisbury constituency, including Tata Chemicals Europe Ltd. and Compass Minerals UK Ltd.</p><p> </p><p>Following a route decision in autumn 2016 HS2 Ltd will begin production of a full Environmental Impact Assessment.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:35:46.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515450/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515450/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what work HS2 Ltd has carried out in Eddisbury constituency since 17 July 2013 on mapping unmapped (a) pipework, (b) brine wells and (c) other brine extraction infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515451","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>According to the Department for Transport’s records, representatives from HS2 Ltd met with King Street Energy on 25 September 2013 and 22nd May 2014 to discuss interactions with the proposed HS2 route.</p><p> </p><p>A further meeting between HS2 Ltd and King Street Energy is scheduled to take place later this year.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:18:46.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515451/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515451/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Northwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on whether there have been any meetings between HS2 Ltd and King Street Energy Ltd to discuss the proposed gas storage project near Northwich.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515452","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>HS2 Ltd has commissioned from a mining engineer (in consultation with the Cheshire Brine Subsidence Compensation Board) a study of the saltfield, which applies to Cheshire including the Eddisbury constituency.</p><p><br>HS2 Ltd. has commissioned from Heriot-Watt University a modelling of the geodynamic effects of high speed railway operation, which applies route wide including the Eddisbury constituency.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:14:03.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515452/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515452/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what research HS2 Ltd has (a) produced and (b) commissioned on the geological effect of the construction and operation of High Speed 2 in Eddisbury constituency.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515453","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-03","<p>As of 30 March 2016 £280,573,795 has been paid to residents under the statutory blight regime and the HS2 discretionary schemes.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-03T13:30:09.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515453/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515453/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on the total amount of compensation payments agreed for residents along the route of the High Speed 2 line to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","35371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515454","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>No specific estimates have been made for the cost of construction or dealing with engineering issues arising from salt within the Eddisbury constituency, however the cost of construction of this section of HS2 and risk provision for engineering issues arising from salt has been included in the overall funding envelope which was confirmed in November 2015.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T12:59:08.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515454/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515454/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost of (a) construction of High Speed 2 through Eddisbury constituency and (b) dealing with engineering issues arising from salt mining, brine extraction or subsistence in such construction.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515455","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>HS2 Ltd have not produced any detailed work specifically examining the potential effect of the construction of High Speed Two on the aquifer in Eddisbury.</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Ltd has commissioned desktop studies using existing survey work for the whole of the route from Crewe to Manchester which will examine interactions with landfill and mining and other ground conditions.</p><p> </p><p>Following a route decision in autumn 2016 HS2 Ltd will begin production of a full Environmental Impact Assessment.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T13:07:05.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515455/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515455/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Eddisbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what research HS2 Ltd has (a) produced and (b) commissioned since 17 July 2013 on the potential effect of the construction of High Speed 2 on the aquifer in Eddisbury.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515456","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>The following Natura 2000 sites within 10 miles of the proposed Phase 2 Route (Special Protection Areas (<em><em>SPAs</em></em>) and Special Areas of Conservation (<em><em>SACs</em></em>)) have been identified:</p><p> </p><p>1 SPA site</p><p>17 SAC sites</p><p> </p><p><strong>SPA Name </strong></p><p>Peak District Moors</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>SAC Name </strong></p><p>Birklands &amp; Bilhaugh</p><p>Cannock Chase</p><p>Cannock Extension Canal</p><p>Denby Grange Colliery Ponds</p><p>Ensor's Pool</p><p>Kirk Deighton</p><p>Manchester Mosses</p><p>Mottey Meadows</p><p>Oak Mere</p><p>Pasturefields Salt Marsh</p><p>Peak District Dales</p><p>River Mease</p><p>Rixton Clay Pits</p><p>Rochdale Canal</p><p>Skipwith Common</p><p>South Pennine Moors</p><p>West Midlands Mosses</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-05-04T12:55:52.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515456/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515456/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which Natura 2000 sites have been identified as being within 10 miles of the proposed Phase 2 route of High Speed Two.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","35398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515457","Department for Transport","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Department for Transport is committed to building transport networks which work for everyone, ensuring that disabled people have the same access to transport services as non-disabled members of society</p><p> </p><p>Compliance with bus accessibility Regulations was 89% in England in 2015; while 60% of rail vehicles, up from 46% in 2013, were built or fully refurbished to modern access standards.</p><p> </p><p>By the end of this year Access for All will have completed more than 150 step-free routes at rail stations against a target of 125. More than 1,200 stations have received smaller scale improvements. To build on this success £160m has been allocated to another 68 stations to be delivered by 2019.</p><p> </p><p>We plan to require that taxi and private hire vehicle drivers provide assistance to wheelchair users and refrain from charging extra by commencing sections 165 and 167 of the Equality Act 2010 by the end of the year.</p><p> </p><p>The Department works closely with its statutory advisors on the needs of disabled people, the Disabled Persons’ Transport Advisory Committee, such as on a project to develop best practice guidance on the delivery of disability awareness training for bus and coach drivers.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-05-04T12:47:55.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515457/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515457/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-25","Transport: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department has taken to encourage transport operators to provide services that are accessible to disabled people.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","35352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515458","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Following the first tier tribunal decision that the Universal Credit risk register for April 2012 should be released, the document was shared with the requestor.</p><p>The government’s view remains that is not in the public interest to publish risk registers because it will compromise the ability to conduct a full and frank assessment of risks and therefore increase the risk to successful delivery of major programmes<em>.</em></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T09:55:56.643Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515458/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515458/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2016 to Question 30624 and with reference to the First-Tier Tribunal General Regulatory Chamber Information Rights decision of 11 March 2016, if his Department will publish the Risk Register prior to the universal credit re-set in 2013.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515459","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Copies of the communications claimants received have been placed in the House of Commons library (reference DEP2016-0302) and are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2016-03-11&amp;search_term=Department+for+Work+and+Pensions&amp;itemId=119004#toggle-302" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2016-03-11&amp;search_term=Department+for+Work+and+Pensions&amp;itemId=119004#toggle-302</a></p><p> </p><p>The correspondence does not inform claimants of the availability of the Flexible Support Fund, however guidance for Work Coaches has been updated to remind them of the availability of the fund for those claimants affected by the changes to the Work Allowances.</p><p> </p><p>The approximate cost to DWP of communicating the planned changes to the work allowances to Universal Credit claimants was £590,000.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","35355 ; 35356","2016-05-04T10:47:58.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515459/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515459/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 March 2016 to Question 30180 on universal credit: correspondence, whether claimants have been informed of the availability of the Flexible Support Fund in that correspondence.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515460","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Copies of the communications claimants received have been placed in the House of Commons library (reference DEP2016-0302) and are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2016-03-11&amp;search_term=Department+for+Work+and+Pensions&amp;itemId=119004#toggle-302" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2016-03-11&amp;search_term=Department+for+Work+and+Pensions&amp;itemId=119004#toggle-302</a></p><p> </p><p>The correspondence does not inform claimants of the availability of the Flexible Support Fund, however guidance for Work Coaches has been updated to remind them of the availability of the fund for those claimants affected by the changes to the Work Allowances.</p><p> </p><p>The approximate cost to DWP of communicating the planned changes to the work allowances to Universal Credit claimants was £590,000.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","35354 ; 35356","2016-05-04T10:47:58.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515460/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515460/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 11 March 2016 to Question 30180, when he expects copies of the correspondence sent to claimants on universal credit to be placed in the Library.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515461","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Copies of the communications claimants received have been placed in the House of Commons library (reference DEP2016-0302) and are available at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2016-03-11&amp;search_term=Department+for+Work+and+Pensions&amp;itemId=119004#toggle-302" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/business-papers/commons/deposited-papers/?fd=2016-03-11&amp;search_term=Department+for+Work+and+Pensions&amp;itemId=119004#toggle-302</a></p><p> </p><p>The correspondence does not inform claimants of the availability of the Flexible Support Fund, however guidance for Work Coaches has been updated to remind them of the availability of the fund for those claimants affected by the changes to the Work Allowances.</p><p> </p><p>The approximate cost to DWP of communicating the planned changes to the work allowances to Universal Credit claimants was £590,000.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","35354 ; 35355","2016-05-04T10:47:58.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515461/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515461/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 33701, how much his Department has spent on contacting people likely to be affected by planned changes to the work allowance element of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515462","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>The events that can trigger a change of circumstances depend on many factors. They are similar to the circumstances that would trigger a new claim to existing benefits or tax credits.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T09:48:57.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515462/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515462/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 25156, if he will publish the list of circumstances that would trigger natural migration from tax credits to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515463","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>A total of 337 new employees were appointed to the Department for Work and Pensions during the period 21 March 2016 to 25 April 2016.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T09:03:36.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515463/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515463/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Department for Work and Pensions: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many new staff have been appointed to his Department since 21 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515464","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>Estimates of the number of recipients of the State Pension living overseas in each of the last 10 years are published on the DWP Tabulation Tool. The numbers from November 2012 can be seen in the column ‘Claimants living abroad’, and prior to this in the column ‘Unknown’ of this table:</p><p><a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/sp/ccdate/ccgor/a_carate_r_ccdate_c_ccgor.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/sp/ccdate/ccgor/a_carate_r_ccdate_c_ccgor.html</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T13:20:04.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515464/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515464/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the number of recipients of the state pension living overseas in each of the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","35421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515465","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>All three statutory maintenance schemes allow the Secretary of State to revise any maintenance liability decision found to be incorrect as a result of misrepresentation by either parent. There is no timescale within which the misrepresentation must be discovered, before a revision may be completed.</p><p> </p><p>Under the 2012 scheme, in the first instance maintenance is assessed using historic income information from HMRC. Annual reviews are carried out using HMRC income data and liabilities are adjusted accordingly. Over the lifetime of a case changes to income should therefore be reflected appropriately.</p><p> </p><p>Where an individual is assessed on current income, they are obliged to inform the Child Maintenance Service of any increase to their income of 25% or over. If they fail to do so and the Child Maintenance Service subsequently becomes aware of an increase in their income, the Secretary of State may still calculate a new assessment, taking effect at the point the income increased.</p><p> </p><p>Any arrears that result from such “retrospective” action will nonetheless be due and CMS will take enforcement action if the Paying Parent does not arrange to pay them themselves. The CMS has a comprehensive range of enforcement actions at its disposal, to help ensure that parents fulfil their obligations.</p><p> </p><p>All maintenance liability decisions carry an underlying right of appeal to an independent Tribunal.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T14:37:00.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515465/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515465/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what mechanisms his Department has put in place for redress and backdated payments to the parent with care in the event that it is found that the non-resident parent (a) provided false information about their income and  (b) failed to inform the relevant body of an increase in their income under (i) the Child Support Agency scheme and (ii) the Child Maintenance Service scheme; and what the timescales are for such redress or payments.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","35379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515466","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>The savings were estimated using DWP's and HMRC's models of the tax and benefit system. Extracting the full details of the calculations carried out within the models would only be possible at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-28T09:35:26.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515466/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515466/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 10 of the explanatory memorandum to the Universal Credit (Work Allowance) Amendment Regulations 2015, if he will publish the calculations used to estimate savings arising from the introduction of those regulations.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515467","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>We only collect information that is relevant for an online service. As information on honours is not needed for a user to complete any of our online services we have no plans to collect this information.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-04T16:02:51.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515467/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515467/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Department for Work and Pensions: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34465, if his Department will take steps to allow web-users to include honours when completing Government online forms.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","35211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515468","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>I replied to the hon. Member on 21 April 2016.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T07:25:34.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515468/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515468/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for  Pontypridd of 15 April 2016 on assessments for personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515469","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>Improving support for disabled people and people with health conditions to get into and stay in work is a key priority for Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has outlined that he is starting a new conversation with disabled people and people with health conditions, their representatives, healthcare professionals and employers. He is listening to all of their ideas and this will help inform our plans.</p><p> </p><p>These will be set out in due course.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T13:15:52.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515469/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515469/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 22 March 2016 to Question 30765, when his Department plans to publish its White Paper on improving support for disabled people.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515470","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Analysis undertaken by DWP has identified a large number of variables that will affect debt repayments from individuals claiming Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>This includes, but is not limited to; the number of people claiming Universal Credit, the level of Universal Credit award they receive, the amount of debt they have (across DWP, HMRC and Local Authorities), the approach for recovering debt from Universal Credit and the approach for recovering debt by deduction from earnings.</p><p> </p><p>Considering this, it is likely that most Universal Credit claimants with existing debts or debt repayment arrangements will be affected to some degree. At present there is insufficient data to predict the effects of these variables accurately.</p><p> </p><p>Given the scale of the change, the likely confidence interval for forecasts for any time after 2016-17 is too large to give a meaningful or indicative answer at this time.</p><p> </p><p>However, as Universal Credit rolls out, DWP will continue to analyse all available data to give a wider view on any changes to debt repayment agreements that are being seen under Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, DWP will continue to work with HMRC and Local Authorities in developing forecasting models to show the changes that people with debt will see as their benefit payments move to Universal Credit.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-04T15:57:58.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515470/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515470/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the number of people who will be affected by proposed changes to debt repayment arrangements under universal credit.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515471","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Government recognises that some families on low incomes can struggle to meet the costs of a funeral, this is why the Social Fund Funeral Expenses Payments covers specified necessary costs and provides a significant contribution of up to £700 towards the fee levied by funeral directors for all other funeral expenses.</p><p>My Department continues to look at the effectiveness of the scheme so that it provides effective support and will keep on monitoring its effectiveness and liaising with stakeholders and interested groups so that it maintains its aim of providing a contribution towards the cost of a funeral.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-04T16:34:28.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515471/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515471/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Funeral Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 33700, what steps his Department is taking to monitor levels of funeral poverty.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515472","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Jobcentre Plus Work Coaches undertake outreach work every day in local communities on a number of activities which includes supporting the Troubled Families Programme, homeless hostels, drug and alcohol dependency and ex-offenders. They have recently been helping people with back-to-work support and advice in Manchester at the Lalley Community Centre, where a food bank sits alongside other support services.</p><p> </p><p>The decision on engagement with food banks and other local community initiatives will continue to remain at local discretion; where Jobcentre Plus is invited to work with a food bank provider and where there is local need.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T10:32:14.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515472/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515472/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Jobcentre Plus: Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 18 April 2016 to Question 33196, whether his Department plans to place work coaches in other food banks.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515473","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>The security of claimant information is a crucial part of the way that data is managed in the department. The personal details of Universal Credit claimants are securely stored and access to this data is strictly controlled. A range of controls are present within the Universal Credit service to protect the confidentiality and integrity of claimant personal data and there are regular tests against these controls to ensure that they meet Government and international security standards.</p><p>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T10:00:24.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515473/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515473/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the personal details of universal credit claimants are stored safely.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515474","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Flexible Support Fund allocation for 2016-17 is £64m. This figure is subject to change throughout the year.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T15:19:12.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515474/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515474/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Flexible Support Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2016 to Question 26246, what funding his Department has allocated to the Flexible Support Fund in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515475","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>The Secretary of State has met with a number of his constituents who have raised this issue, and he will be meeting with Tim Loughton, who has been involved in the WASPI campaign, very soon. He is clear that there are no plans to change policy.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-05-04T13:41:48.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515475/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515475/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Women Against State Pension Inequality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will meet representatives of the Women Against State Pension Inequality campaign.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515476","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>I refer the hon.Member to the answer I gave on 1 February 2016 to <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;dept=29&amp;uin=24981" target="_blank">24981</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T13:09:49.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515476/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515476/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Pension Protection Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons the Government has not yet implemented its policy to increase the Pension Protection Fund compensation cap for service over 20 years; and when he plans to implement that policy.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","35275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515477","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>Work on the changes needed to secondary legislation in relation to the Pension Protection Fund long service cap has begun. I am not, at this stage, able to say when these changes will be brought forward.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T15:19:52.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515477/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515477/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Pensions Act 2014","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2016 to Question 23225, what progress his Department has made on bringing forward changes to secondary legislation that are necessary to implement the relevant provisions of the Pensions Act 2014.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","35312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515478","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T13:12:52.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515478/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515478/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Carer's Allowance: Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people are in receipt of carer's allowance where the person cared for is a stroke survivor.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","35340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515479","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Latest statistics show that 80,830 new businesses have been set up with the support of the New Enterprise Allowance (NEA).</p><p> </p><p>A survey of NEA recipients was published in January 2016 and found that of businesses that had started trading following receipt of NEA support, four in five were still trading giving a sustainability rate of 80%. Of these, over nine in ten had been trading for over 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>This report was published on 28 January and can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/new-enterprise-allowance-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/new-enterprise-allowance-survey</a>.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-05-04T14:46:34.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515479/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515479/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","New Enterprise Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of the New Enterprise Allowance in achieving its aims.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","35319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515480","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>The ‘save and return’ functionality is available in the Universal Credit Full Service because the Full Service has all the security features necessary to safeguard the claimant’s data, by confirming the identity of the returning user.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-28T09:43:45.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515480/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515480/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 21 April 2016 to Question 34466, for what reason a save function is only available as part of the universal credit full service.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","35331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515481","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-28","<p>In England and Wales, the Fit fir Work contract was awarded on the 25<sup>th</sup> July 2014 for a period of 5 years. DWP continues to undertake contract management with the supplier. In Scotland, the service is delivered via an agency agreement with the Scottish Government, made in November 2015 and reviewed annually.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-28T14:00:53.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515481/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515481/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 April 2016 to Question 33647, whether he plans to continue the Fit for Work programme for the full length of the contract.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","35332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515482","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Departmental preparations for the reform of non-departmental public bodies take account of the <em>Checklist for Departments</em> published by the Cabinet Office, which includes advice on pensions.</p><p> </p><p>In the past five years, the Department has reformed three bodies which employed staff.</p><p> </p><p>In two cases, staff pensions were provided by the Civil Service Pension Scheme, which has established procedures in place for identifying pensioners as they become eligible, and ensuring that payments are processed on time:</p><p> </p><p>The Child Maintenance and Enforcement Commission was abolished on 31 July 2012 and employed 7,652 full time equivalent staff, all of whom were civil servants;</p><p>The Independent Living Fund legally closed on 30 June 2015, however a small residual team of 15 staff was retained until 30 September to deal with any residual closure issues. It had previously employed 99.5 full time equivalent staff.</p><p> </p><p>In April 2015, the Remploy business was sold to a new company outside Government control. The majority of its employees transferred to that company and left the Remploy Pension Scheme at the time. The pension scheme continues to be managed by its trustees and the scheme administrators, who remain responsible for identifying pensioners and ensuring they are paid appropriately once they become eligible. At 1 January 2016, the Remploy Pension Scheme had approximately 18,000 members, of whom over 9,500 were deferred members and thus potential future pensioners. From 1 April 2016, my Department is now the Principal Employer for this scheme.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","35491","2016-05-04T13:22:24.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515482/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515482/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-25","Non-departmental Public Bodies: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the efficiency of the pension schemes of abolished non-departmental public bodies in (a) identifying pensioners as they become eligible for payments and (b) ensuring that payments are processed and triggered for payment on the due date.","false","Biography information for Mike Weir","Angus","Mike Weir","35483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515483","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-05-04","<p>Departmental preparations for the reform of non-departmental public bodies take account of the <em>Checklist for Departments</em> published by the Cabinet Office, which includes advice on pensions.</p><p> </p><p>In the past five years, the Department has reformed three bodies which employed staff.</p><p> </p><p>In two cases, staff pensions were provided by the Civil Service Pension Scheme, which has established procedures in place for identifying pensioners as they become eligible, and ensuring that payments are processed on time:</p><p> </p><p>The Child Maintenance and Enforcement Commission was abolished on 31 July 2012 and employed 7,652 full time equivalent staff, all of whom were civil servants;</p><p>The Independent Living Fund legally closed on 30 June 2015, however a small residual team of 15 staff was retained until 30 September to deal with any residual closure issues. It had previously employed 99.5 full time equivalent staff.</p><p> </p><p>In April 2015, the Remploy business was sold to a new company outside Government control. The majority of its employees transferred to that company and left the Remploy Pension Scheme at the time. The pension scheme continues to be managed by its trustees and the scheme administrators, who remain responsible for identifying pensioners and ensuring they are paid appropriately once they become eligible. At 1 January 2016, the Remploy Pension Scheme had approximately 18,000 members, of whom over 9,500 were deferred members and thus potential future pensioners. From 1 April 2016, my Department is now the Principal Employer for this scheme.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","35483","2016-05-04T13:22:24.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515483/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/515483/answer",,,,,"2