"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514715","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>Electoral registers are compiled and maintained locally by Electoral Registration Officers primarily for the purposes of running Parliamentary and local elections in their area. A centralised, national electoral register would not necessarily help them do this, and would potentially create concerns about how government handles citizens personal data, so we have made no assessment of this kind.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-04-26T12:00:36.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514715/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514715/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-21","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of the feasibility of introducing a centralised, national electoral register.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","35075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514716","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-04-26T15:26:58.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514716/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514716/answer","UKSA response to 35043.pdf","UKSA response to 35043.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - EEA Member State Migration","UKSA Letter to Member - EEA Member State Migration","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514716/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-21","Immigrants: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many nationals of other EEA member states migrated to the UK with dependants of school age in each of the last 10 years; and how many school-aged dependants of other EEA member states have lived in the UK in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","35043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514717","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>Departments are currently working with grant recipients on the implementation of the guidance, in relation to the new grants clause. This will include a consideration of equality impact issues, which will be reported centrally to the Cabinet Office for assessment, with regards to finalising the central policy by 1 May 2016.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-26T14:44:19.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514717/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514717/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-21","Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether an equality impact assessment has been undertaken in respect of the policy of including an anti-lobbying clause in government grant agreements.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","35054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514718","Department for Education","false","2016-04-29","<p>In January 2015 there were 1,198,494 children known to be eligible for and claiming free school meals. All these children were in households whose income was below the threshold for receiving free school meals.</p><p>We do not hold any information on the nationality of the parents of these children.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-04-29T09:48:58.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514718/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514718/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514718/answer/previousversion/57683","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","60","Education","Education","2016-04-21","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of children in households whose income is below the threshold for receiving free school meals; and how many such children have at least one parent who is a national from another EEA member state.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","William Wragg","35039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514719","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-28","<p>The composition of the most senior collective leadership body (now Civil Service Board) has changed markedly since 2010 and its membership is reviewed on an ongoing basis. The Board has existed in its current guise, under the Chairmanship of the Cabinet Secretary, since September 2014. During the past year six new Board members have been appointed, replacing those who have left the Civil Service. The current membership can be found here (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/civil-service/about/our-governance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/civil-service/about/our-governance</a>).</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-28T09:39:39.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514719/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514719/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-21","Civil Service Board","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what changes in personnel there have been on the Civil Service Board since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","35010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514720","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>There is no current plan for Government to consult on setting up a Commissioner for Older Persons.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-05-04T16:32:57.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514720/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514720/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-21","Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if the Government will consult on setting up a Commissioner for Older People.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","35009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514721","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-27","<p>HM Treasury has taken note of this feasibility study. Professor Sir Charles Bean’s Independent Review of Economic Statistics highlighted the importance of proper measurement of the sharing economy and to enable the Office for National Statistics to develop world-leading analytical and digital capabilities in economic measurement, the government will invest over £10m in a new hub for data science and a centre for excellence in economic measurement in line with recommendations.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-27T12:22:20.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514721/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514721/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-21","Sharing Economy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the report by the Office for National Statistics, the Feasibility of measuring the sharing economy, published in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","35007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514722","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-27","<p>According to the latest figures published by the Office for National Statistics, UK house price growth moderated to 7.6% in the year to February 2016, down from a peak of 12.1% in September 2014. A number of factors are likely to have supported demand for housing in recent years, including low interest rates.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has established the independent Financial Policy Committee (FPC) within the Bank of England, designed to monitor risks to the UK financial system and take action to address those where appropriate. The FPC has been given the authority and a powerful set of tools to tackle the risks posed to financial stability from the housing market.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-27T12:23:49.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514722/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514722/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-21","Housing: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of low long-term real interest rates on house prices.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","35008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514723","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-29","<p>The “HM Treasury analysis: the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives” uses the ONS central projection of total net international migration, defined as the movement of people to or from countries outside of the UK. As such, it applies to citizens of all countries outside the UK, including Turkey, Montenegro and Serbia.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-29T09:16:10.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514723/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514723/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-21","Migration","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 136 of the publication, HM Treasury analysis: the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives, published in April 2016, whether the total net international migration figure of 185,000 per year from 2021 includes (a) Turkey, (b) Montenegro and (c) Serbia.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","35005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514724","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-26","<p>The soft drinks industry levy is part of the government’s strategy to tackle childhood obesity. It is aimed at encouraging producers to reformulate their product mix and move consumers towards lower sugar alternatives.</p><p> </p><p>The levy is expected to raise £520 million in the first year across the UK; the OBR expect that this number will fall over time as producers reformulate their product mix and consumption of high sugar drinks decreases. In England, the revenue will be used to double the primary school PE and sport premium; provide funding to give 25% of secondary schools increased opportunity to extend their school day to offer a wider range of activities for pupils; and fund the expansion of breakfast clubs in up to 1,600 schools.</p><p> </p><p>As stated at Budget 2016, the Barnett Formula will continue to be applied to spending on these new initiatives in the normal way.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-04-26T13:43:49.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514724/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514724/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-21","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the amount which the soft drinks industry levy will raise for public expenditure in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","35001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514725","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-26","<p>Reporting on asset sales is made on a financial year basis in departmental accounts. Details of any specific historic asset sales can be found in announcements made at the time of sale.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-04-26T16:26:19.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514725/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514725/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-21","Government: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the total receipts from Government asset sales were in each financial year from 1986 to 2009.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","34989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514726","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-29","<p>The Chancellor announced the Cyber Innovation Centre for Cheltenham in November 2015, helping to ensure Cheltenham remains a world leader in cyber excellence. The Department for Culture, Media and Sport will be running a competitive tender process to invite providers to run the centre to ensure that this initiative delivers the best possible value for money. We will disclose the budget when the tender exercise has completed, which we anticipate will be this autumn.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-04-29T13:49:13.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514726/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514726/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-21","Cyber Innovation Centre: Cheltenham","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the budget is for the Cyber Innovation Centre in Cheltenham.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","35084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514727","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Government intends to move to 100 per cent business rates retention in England by the end of this Parliament. The new system will have stronger incentives to boost growth, and areas that take bold decisions to further increase growth will see the benefits. We will be giving councils the power to cut the business rates multiplier to improve the business environment for enterprise and attract further businesses to their area. But we recognise that not all councils are the same. In setting up this system we will ensure that there is redistribution between councils so that areas do not lose out just because they currently collect less in local business rates, and will put protections in place for authorities that see their business rates income fall significantly.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-28T09:29:49.79Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514727/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514727/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-21","Non-domestic Rates: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he has made an assessment of the potential effect of the devolution of business rates on business growth in (a) former steel works and coalfield areas and (b) other local authority areas with a depleted industrial base.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","35079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514728","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Government is open to discussing any devolution proposals that include strong, accountable governance arrangements. But we have been clear—the most ambitious, far-reaching powers and responsibilities will be offered only to those areas that provide a directly-elected, single point of accountability.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-04-26T10:59:51.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514728/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514728/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-21","Combined Authorities: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether there are any circumstances under which a devolution deal with a combined authority will be undertaken without an elected mayor being proposed.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","35104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514729","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-26","<p>Devolution deals, including commitments for mayoral governance, are negotiated and agreed with those democratically elected to represent their area, and who are accountable to their local electorate.</p><p>This Department has not undertaken direct public consultations on this matter in Cheshire and Warrington.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-04-26T10:51:25.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514729/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514729/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-21","Mayors: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many public consultations his Department has conducted on the subject of mayors in Cheshire and Warrington since 2010.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","35057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514730","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-26","<p>Cheshire and Warrington were one of 38 areas across the country to submit devolution deal proposals in September 2015. Devolution deal proposals are developed and led by local areas. Therefore, the decision to release information regarding the content of any submission—including governance objectives—is a matter for the local area to decide, not the Government.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-04-26T10:56:11.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514730/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514730/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-21","Mayors: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations he has received in favour of elected mayors in Cheshire and Warrington.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","35058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514731","Department of Health","false","2016-04-29","<p>Monitoring food businesses to ensure compliance with legislation on food labelling and composition is the responsibility of county councils, unitary authorities, the London Boroughs and some but not all metropolitan borough councils. These local authorities are also responsible for taking enforcement action, including prosecutions, where non-compliance is found.</p><p>Data is reported to the Food Standards Agency (FSA) on the number of food analyses undertaken in relation to compositional issues and labelling and presentation issues; 23,599 analyses were undertaken in 2014/15, 16,899 for compositional issues and 6,700 for labelling and presentation issues.</p><p>Data is also reported to the FSA on the total number of prosecutions concluded for food standards issues. This includes action in relation to composition, labelling and presentation but also for other issues such as chemical contamination. In 2014/15, 75 United Kingdom food establishments were subject to prosecution.</p><p>The FSA has recently established a central register of successful food law prosecutions. Data collected for the first year of operation of the register is not yet complete, but in future it will provide more definitive data on prosecutions for offences of this nature.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-29T12:42:33.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514731/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514731/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-21","Food: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) incidents have been reported to trading standards teams of and (b) prosecutions have taken place for food with falsely-labelled ingredients in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","35064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514732","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-29","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not collect or publish data on emergency traveller sites.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-04-29T11:47:46.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514732/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/514732/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-21","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many emergency traveller sites there are in England; and how many of those sites are operational.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","35031"
